== Description ==
{{Blurimage|file=Level4Workrooms1.png|caption=A typical workroom, lined with desks.|hovertext=Barren.}}'''Level 4''' is a sprawling complex of barren rooms and cubicles, resembling a modern commercial office building. Most rooms in the level are featureless and empty, although indents throughout the carpeting suggest that furniture may have been present at some point in time. Many of the fluorescent lights on the ceiling do not function, with their power switches missing from the walls.

Since the level lacks any inherent danger, environmental or otherwise, it is generally regarded as a safe haven among wanderers. Strewn about are vending machines containing a variety of items such as [[Object 1|Almond Water]], [[Object 5|Greek Fire]], and [[Objects|other articles]] of varying utility. Strangely, although the multiple stairwells throughout the level suggest the existence of multiple floors, using them to ascend or descend floors has been reported to simply lead back to the same floor. In rare cases, it is possible to enter [[Level 4.3|certain levels]] using such methods, though this is seldom in occurrence and is not a reliable method of exit.

{{Blurimage|file=Level4altbg.png|caption=A smaller, empty office. The lights are switched on, an aspect not shared with the level's larger rooms.|hovertext=Busy, yet not busy.|align=left}}
It is theorized that '''Level 4''' resides within [[The Void]], as it contains multiple points of entry into it. Although a vast majority of unconventional egress points lead into The Void itself, rare cases have reported accidental entry into [[The Broken|worse]] [[Waste Disposal|locations]] as a result of unsystematic exits or botched no-clips. Furthermore, research suggests that the "sky" visible from the windows is entirely artificial, as the clouds and time of day are stationary and do not change.

'''Level 4''' is quieter than other levels in the Main Nine, with the only ambient noise present being the heavy pattering of rain on the windows. The enclosed structure of the level causes the sounds to have a light echo — making the sound universally heard across the entire level, regardless of one's location. Other than this, the only other naturally occurring sound within '''Level 4''' is the moderately loud rumbling of pipes, similar to what one would hear on [[Level 2]] and [[Level 3]].

The false sky within the inaccessible outside area of '''Level 4''' remains in a constant, acute downpour, with a thick layer of fog making it impossible to see past a few meters. Despite the stationary weather, it is possible for events such as thunderstorms and blizzards to occur — though these are seldom. The climate within the level retains a constant oscillation between 12°C to 18°C (54° to 64°F) throughout the course of several hours. It is theorized that such torrential rain is a result of water vapor acclimating within The Void, retaining a constant humid climate in the level's exterior.

'''Level 4''' is one of few levels to possess Euclidean geometry; with linear travel being the most effective method of exploration. The level has a relatively confined size compared to other levels, measuring around 120,000km<sup>2</sup> (74,560mi<sup>2</sup>), making it possible to locate other wanderers within the level. As these aspects make the level an ideal location for many wanderers, the total population of '''Level 4''' is estimated to be somewhere in the tens, if not hundreds of thousands.<center><div style="display: inline-block; text-align: center; background:rgba (0, 0, 0, 0); border: double 4.5px white; margin: 0px; padding-top:-500px; padding-bottom:-500px; padding-left:-500px; padding-right:-500px;">[[File:Liminal_Office.jpg|link=|center|800x800px]]</div></center><center>Another image of '''Level 4'''.</center>{{Underline}}Many areas of '''Level 4''' are populated by smaller rooms, typically consisting of workrooms, hallways, and confined offices. Whilst the larger, more open areas of the level are entirely bereft of large furniture and appliances, these smaller rooms are starkly different, containing furniture unlike most other areas. Such appliances include desks and desktop computers of [[BackOS|questionable quality]], as well as partly functional fluorescent lighting, among other things. Other amenities include emergency exits, elevators, and mysterious trapdoors, though most of which lead [[The Void|seemingly nowhere]].

== Addendum ==
<div style="text-align: center; background:rgba (0, 0, 0, 0); border: double 4.5px white; padding: 10px;"><center><big><big>'''''Record 1E-7:'''''</big></big>
"Collapse"
</center>
----Roman was never a cooperative person. His idea of a good time was climbing into closing buildings and getting high amongst the remains of human life. Though on the days he couldn't run away from his problems, he was stale and unenthusiastic. Slaving away at the untold hours and begging the stars above for a break. It wouldn't be enough just to have an extra day off, he wanted the world gone for even a little while. The cannabis inside the ass-cracks of human civilization was just one way of doing it. And like all the days before, when he had time to disappear from his stuffy office, he drove back to the abandoned building.

It was cold and dead inside, with echoes of an industry now laid to waste, an open scar on the modern world. It's what the yellow tape was for outside, but he'd seen squatters fight tooth and nail to keep the building up, and if they didn't get their way, his chance to hide away from the world would be taken alongside it. With the hours he had left, he spent his time there, speaking to the husky and musky blemishes on civilization like they were actually people.

"How was work?" One of them started, a stout and oddly plump woman whose stiff movements oddly reminded Roman of a marionette doll. His hands were kept over a barreled fire, crackling as the only source of light in the dinghy building. Roman had attempted to switch his lighter on, to no avail.

"Fuckin' bitch," he muttered to himself, toying with the lighter until it eventually clicked to life, lighting the cigar he held firmly between his teeth. "Not you, by the way. It's this damn lighter," he chimed whilst twiddling the cigar with his fingers.

"Work was fine, it sucked. But not enough to quit yet." Roman mused, looking over to the destitute. While he wanted to question the other on what to him would even be a bad job, he held his tongue tightly. There was no benefit to a rude choice of words, especially since he was here to support someone. Someone who was finally like him, just a little farther gone than he would expect. The vagrant scoffed, and the uneasy bubbling of a kitchen pot turned his attention away from the flame. The bubbling would start to boil as both quickly moved over to it. Roman, the larger and more able man, picked it up, sighing as his friend put the fire out.
{{Collapse|num=Portul1|final=|initial=[[File:Flashlight2.png|center]]|body=<center><big><big>'''''CRUNCH'''''</big></big></center>
<br>
The two jolted as their eyes swerved to a barrel now imploded, the fire rapidly hushed as it seemed to fall into the navy basin. With the mania, Roman's hand twitched, pouring the boiling water on himself. His screams were agonizingly loud, before being clamped by the other, only lowly whimpering into her dirty hands. His lower body shook and shuddered, as walking turned into an oozing lurch. The burning fluids of both oil and water leached past his pants and socks leaving his skin red and gooey. The bum, acting quickly, took Roman to sit at the only open table. “I’m sorry…” 

“Eh,” she started, shrugging as she picked up the pot, the mixed package of noodles now sloppy and wet discards on the floor. “More likely you’re going to need medical attention.”

“NO!” Roman shouts, grabbing his phone tightly. 

“Give me it.” She glared, even if it would cripple Roman fiscally, having 2 legs was better than barely having half of each. The minor scuffle didn’t last long, as Roman chucked his mobile into the blend of city and forest. A muted crack echoed her ire, only sighing. “Well, until we can get you to the hospital then, you’re staying with me, alright? And I’m gon’ make you put those bum legs to use unless they kill you.”

Roman, barely even conflicted about no longer working, nodded. 

{{Collapse|num=Portul2|final=
|initial=[[File:Flashlight2.png|center]]
|body= He found peace in being a reject. Learning quickly the other lazarus’ name is Ellie. As he learned to work in what would soon become an amalgam of lesser muscle and flesh. It sank to his ankles, leaving them needing to cover the upper half and median of his body with heavy cloth. It sure wasn’t enough though, as the parts soon grew festering and bleak. 

Yet, perhaps it was a greater sign of his lunacy, Roman never cared. He poured his last bits of cash on cigarettes, and each time his body ached and burned, he’d suck down another blunt till the pain couldn’t be deciphered. Ellie wasn't much a fan of his trashiness, as he was the one who kept food coming to her, even if it was at the end of a crummy job. It was funding. For her, that was food money and clothes money, not the droves of cigarettes Roman bought. So she forced him to figure out that part of the deal, and despite his burning legs, he could use them for pity points.

His body became emaciated and his facial hair unkempt, and attempts of forming a relationship were shot dead every time. Roman was only going to stay as long as the wounds remained, and she spent all the time she could looking for the man’s mobile. Perhaps it would save him, no, them, eventually. But she had no means to confirm that. 

It was upon those dusklaid nights, where the empty promises of the sun never striked their skin. One of many days that time around, as the pain in Roman’s legs only seemed to worsen, and the weed was no longer helping. So he sat, dazzed and clearly buzzed. He’d laugh at jokes that never happened, and just staring into the space between atoms, waiting for something new. And today would be just that. Soon their silence was broken by the crumble of the building.

“Did you hear that?”

“...no? I think you might be hearing things.” Ellie nodded at Roman’s comment, sighing aimlessly as she looked back to the old pot. The one that once boiled Roman’s skin, still used to feed them nightly. And as the pot bubbled again, the world seemed to reminded them of what happened last time.

And suddenly. Everything went dark. 

{{Collapse|num=Portul3|final=
|initial=[[File:Flashlight2.png|center]]
|body= Roman’s eyes jolted awake, and the ache of his legs was the first he heard. It was an unbearable violence in a place he was almost familiar with. His bones creaked from the crash, and begged for him to lie still.

Get up.

With the draining power of his arms, he was able to force himself to stand. Welcomed by the mono blue of company complacency. All it was missing was the corny team building posters. His thoughts melted and blended again, lurching him against a window. It was cool to the touch, paned glass coated with droplets of a falling storm, he could barely look beyond the false sky as his vision blurred and he felt the pain seep deeper. It sank into his bones and up his body, moving to his spine and then back to his ankles. His legs only stood by their knees sitting firm. 

And yet that was soon to go out too. Barely looking into the window, lost in both agony and the stripping of cannibis, his word a quiet and meandering slurry,

“Wait, is that... rain? It's been so long since I've last seen daylight.”

